\pard\f0\fs28\qc  {\b 3.           Phyllostachys}                 Siebold & Zucc.
\par

\pard\f0\fs24\qc  By J. do Amaral Franco. 
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 Stems erect; internodes unilaterally flattened and grooved, the groove alternating at each node between the two sides of the stem. Stem-sheaths deciduous. Branches 2 at each node, unequal, patent; sometimes a very small third branch present. Leaves narrowly oblong-lanceolate, relatively small, serrulate on one margin, green above, glaucous beneath. Spikelets with few florets. Stamens 3.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28   A taxonomically difficult genus, of which several species, all from China, are widely cultivated, especially in the W. Mediterranean region. For none of them is there clear evidence of thorough naturalization, but a few can be met with in seminatural vegetation in neglected parks and similar situations. Of these, the following appear to be the most widespread.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  {\b P. nigra} (Loddiges) Munro, {\i Trans. Linn. Soc. London}{\b  26}: 38 (1868). Stems up to 8 m, purplish-black when mature. Leaves 9-15 mm wide.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  {\b P. bambusoides} Siebold & Zucc., {\i Abh. Akad. Wiss.} ({\i München}) {\b 3}: 746 (1843) (incl.{\i  P. quilioi} A. & C. Rivière). Rhizomes short. Stems up to 12(-20) m × 70(-125) mm, green, with basal internodes not conspicuously shorter than those above. Stem-sheaths concolorous, or spotted with purple. Leaves 8-32 mm wide.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  {\b P. aurea} (Carrière) A. & C. Rivière, {\i Bull. Soc. Acclim.} ({\i Paris}) ser.3, {\b 5}: 716 (1878). Like {\i P. bambusoides} but stems pale yellowish-green, with one or more basal internodes much shorter than those above, and with leaves 6-22 mm wide.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  {\b P. viridiglaucescens} (Carrière) A. & C. Rivière, {\i Bambous} 245 (1878). Rhizomes far-creeping. Stems not more than 6 m, very thin-walled, yellowish-green. Stem-sheaths longitudinally striped with purple. Leaves 8-20 mm wide.
\par

